	1️⃣ Storage is the Most Expensive Thing in Solidity
	In the Ethereum network:
	Operation		Gas Cost
	Storage write (new slot)		~20,000 gas
	Storage update		~5,000 gas
	Memory		Very cheap
	Stack		Cheapest
	So rule #1:
	Avoid unnecessary storage writes
	Example (bad):
	uint256 public counter;
	
	function increase() public {
	    counter = counter + 1;
	}
	Better:
	uint256 public counter;
	
	function increase() public {
	    unchecked {
	        counter++;
	    }
	}
	________________________________________
	2️⃣ Why uint256 Can Be Cheaper Than uint8
	Many beginners think smaller types = cheaper.
	❌ Not always true.
	The EVM works in 256-bit words.
	So this:
	uint8 a;
	actually still uses 256 bits internally.
	When you use small integers, Solidity must add extra instructions.
	Example:
	uint8 a = 1;
	a++;
	Compiler adds extra conversion operations.
	So often this is cheaper:
	uint256 a = 1;
	a++;
	✔ That’s why most protocols use uint256 everywhere.
	________________________________________
	3️⃣ Storage Packing (Very Important)
	Each storage slot = 32 bytes
	If variables fit together, Solidity can pack them into one slot.
	Example ❌ (bad):
	uint256 a;
	bool b;
	uint256 c;
	Storage:
	slot1 → a
	slot2 → b
	slot3 → c
	3 storage slots.
	________________________________________
	Better ✅:
	uint256 a;
	uint128 b;
	uint128 c;
	Storage:
	slot1 → a
	slot2 → b + c
	Only 2 slots used.
	________________________________________
	4️⃣ Variable Order Matters
	Bad ordering:
	uint256 a;
	bool b;
	uint256 c;
	Good ordering:
	uint256 a;
	uint256 c;
	bool b;
	Or packing:
	uint128 a;
	uint128 b;
	bool c;
	Compiler packs them.
	________________________________________
	5️⃣ constant and immutable Save Gas
	Example:
	uint256 public constant MAX_SUPPLY = 1_000_000;
	Constant values are stored in bytecode, not storage.
	Cost:
	0 storage gas
	________________________________________
	6️⃣ Use calldata Instead of memory
	Example:
	Bad:
	function set(string memory name) public {}
	Better:
	function set(string calldata name) external {}
	Why?
	calldata = read-only and cheaper
	________________________________________
	7️⃣ Use unchecked for Arithmetic
	Solidity automatically checks overflow.
	Example:
	counter++;
	Compiler adds overflow protection.
	If overflow is impossible:
	unchecked {
	    counter++;
	}
	This saves gas.
	________________________________________
	8️⃣ Use mapping Instead of Arrays (Often)
	Arrays cost more gas when growing.
	Better:
	mapping(address => uint256) balances;
	Instead of:
	address[] users;
	________________________________________
	9️⃣ Batch Operations (Huge Gas Savings)
	ERC-1155 allows batch transfers.
	Example:
	Instead of:
	transfer()
	transfer()
	transfer()
	You do:
	batchTransfer()
	Saving thousands of gas.
