Great! These are real tricks used by senior smart-contract engineers when writing or auditing Solidity code on Ethereum. They mainly help reduce gas costs and improve efficiency.
I’ll explain them simply with examples.
________________________________________
1️⃣ ++i is Cheaper than i++
Both increase the value by 1, but they work slightly differently.
Post-increment
i++;
Meaning:
return i
then increase i
Pre-increment
++i;
Meaning:
increase i
then return i
When the compiler executes i++, it sometimes needs an extra temporary variable.
So in loops, senior developers prefer:
for (uint256 i = 0; i < 10; ++i) {
}
instead of
for (uint256 i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
}
✔ Small gas saving per loop iteration.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Cache Storage Variables in Memory
Accessing storage is expensive.
Example (bad):
for (uint256 i = 0; i < users.length; i++) {
    total += balances[users[i]];
}
Each balances[...] call reads storage again.
Better:
uint256 balance;

for (uint256 i = 0; i < users.length; ++i) {
    balance = balances[users[i]];
    total += balance;
}
✔ Fewer storage reads → less gas.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Cache Array Length
Very common audit optimization.
Bad:
for (uint256 i = 0; i < users.length; i++) {
}
users.length is read every iteration.
Better:
uint256 len = users.length;

for (uint256 i = 0; i < len; ++i) {
}
✔ Saves gas in large loops.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Mapping Trick Used by DeFi Protocols
Protocols like Uniswap and Aave rely heavily on mappings instead of arrays.
Why?
Arrays require iteration to find data.
Example (bad):
address[] users;
To check if a user exists you must loop.
Better:
mapping(address => bool) isUser;
Check instantly:
if (isUser[msg.sender]) {
}
✔ Constant time lookup
✔ No loops
✔ Massive gas savings
________________________________________
5️⃣ One Line That Can Save ~50k Gas
Avoid writing to storage if the value doesn't change.
Bad:
balance[user] = newBalance;
Even if the value is the same.
Better:
if (balance[user] != newBalance) {
    balance[user] = newBalance;
}
Why?
Because a storage write costs:
~20,000 gas
So skipping unnecessary writes saves a lot.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Bonus Trick: Use external Instead of public
Bad:
function setName(string memory name) public {}
Better:
function setName(string calldata name) external {}
Why?
external + calldata = cheaper
Because Solidity doesn't copy data to memory.
________________________________________
🔑 Senior Developer Mindset
When optimizing Solidity on Ethereum, developers think like this:
1️⃣ Avoid storage writes
2️⃣ Minimize storage reads
3️⃣ Use mappings instead of loops
4️⃣ Cache values in memory
5️⃣ Pack variables into 256-bit slots
These tricks are heavily used by protocols like:
	Uniswap
	Aave
because millions of transactions amplify even tiny gas savings.
